She is ready to prove that she and her predecessors have exercised these rights from ancient time without interruption‚ and prays that her claims may be allowed. The Justices consider that before allowing her claims an inquiry should be made as to how the Prioress and her predecessors have exercised their rights. An inquiry is therefore directed, and it is found that the Prioress and her predecessors never at any time had or received for themselves and their tenants housebote and hedgebote, as she claims above, in the woods of North Cave heads and Barley, but that she has for herself and her tenants of Wykeham and Ruston common of pasture for all animals except goats in the same woods, and the moors and woods adjoining, northwards from Yarlesike, and all former Prioresses of that place and their said tenants have used and enjoyed the same right of common so claimed from ancient time without interruption.
